Hands-on RMarkdown session

Let’s learn and practice!

Ieva Rauluseviciute

Date: 2023-11-16

Introduction

RMarkdown is a very useful thing to learn and it can help you:

  • make a nice report on your analysis;
  • create a reproducible workflow;
  • make a tutorial (just like this one);
  • make organized notes when executing code.

In this document I will not list all the syntax or other functionalities of RMarkdown, because this was already covered or there are plenty of recourses online (see bolow). Here we will try to write and execute code.

  

rmarkdown::render(
    "/home/ievarau/Documents/phd/software_quality_seminars/rmarkdown_hands-on/hands_on.Rmd",
    output_format = "html_document")
# rmarkdown::render("input.Rmd", html_document(toc = TRUE, toc_depth = 2))

RMarkdown cheatsheet

RStudio (or now Posit) offers a collection of cheatsheets that I highly recommend. One of them is for RMarkdown.

Other recources

Basic RMarkdown syntax was covered in Software quality session. There are some recources available.

  • this GIT repo with the template document, examples and explanations. It has it’s accompanying SoftFlix episode
  • Some other topics were covered using RMarkdown. For example more advanced ggplot2 plotting session.

Load your libraries

Let’s load libraries.

required.libraries <- c("cowplot",

    suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(lib, character.only = TRUE, quietly = T))

Get your data

You can run bash chunks in here. Make sure you have that engine.opts='-l' parameter.

## Conservation files:
cons_file        <- "example_data/CTCF_conservation.tsv"
random_cons_file <- "example_data/CTCF_conservation_random.tsv"

## Motifs:

core_file     <- "example_data/core_0.txt"

## Motif grammar:
location <- "left"
spacing  <- "13"

Read your data

## Conservation files:
cons   <- data.table::fread(cons_file, header = FALSE)
random <- data.table::fread(random_cons_file, header = FALSE)

df   <- cbind(cons, random[,2])
colnames(df) <- c("dist", "Observed", "Random")

df <- df %>%
    dplyr::select(dist, Observed, Random) %>% 
    gather(key = "Track", value = "value", -dist)

## Motif files:
cobinder_matrix <- data.table::fread(cobinder_file, header = FALSE)
core_matrix     <- data.table::fread(core_file, header = FALSE)

Plot your data

Plotting conservation

colors <- c("#ae017e", "#bdbdbd")

## Conservation base plot:
conservation_plot <- ggplot(
        df, 
        aes(x = dist, y = value)) + 
    geom_line(aes(color = Track)) + 
    scale_color_manual(values = colors) + 
    theme_bw() + 
    xlab("Distance from feature") + 
    ylab("Conservation score") +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
    theme(
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 16, colour = "black"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 14, colour = "black")
    )

Figure 1. Conservation plot 

cobinder_size <- nrow(cobinder_matrix)
core_size     <- nrow(core_matrix)

window_size   <- nrow(random)

core_end   <- (core_size / 2)
core_start <- ((-1 * core_size) / 2)

if (location == "left") {
    spacing       <- (-1 * as.numeric(spacing))
    cobinder_size <- (-1 * cobinder_size)
}

cobinder_end   <- core_start + spacing
cobinder_start <- cobinder_end + cobinder_size

core_segment     <- data.frame(
    x    = core_start,
    xend = core_end,
    y    = 0,
    yend = 0)
cobinder_segment <- data.frame(
    x    = cobinder_start,
    xend = cobinder_end,
    y    = 0,
    yend = 0)
conservation_plot <- conservation_plot +
    geom_segment(data = core_segment,
                aes(x = x, y = y, yend = yend, xend = xend),
                inherit.aes = FALSE,
                colour = "red", linewidth = 2,
                show.legend = NA) +
    geom_segment(data = cobinder_segment,
                aes(x = x, y = y, yend = yend, xend = xend),
                inherit.aes = FALSE,
                colour = "darkgreen", linewidth = 2)

Plotting motif logos

plot_motif <- function(motif_matrix) {
    motif_logo <- ggplot() +
        geom_logo(motif_matrix, method = 'bits', stack_width = 1) +
        theme_logo() +
        scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,2), expand = c(0, 0)) +
        theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
                axis.title.y = element_blank(),
                axis.text.y = element_blank(),
                panel.grid = element_blank(),
                axis.line=element_blank(),
                axis.text = element_blank(),
                axis.ticks=element_blank(),
                axis.title = element_blank(),
                panel.border=element_blank(), 
                panel.spacing = unit(0, "cm"),
                panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
                panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
                plot.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0, "cm"))
    return(motif_logo)
}
## Cobinder matrix:
colnames(cobinder_matrix) <- c("A", "C", "G", "T")
cobinder_matrix <- t(cobinder_matrix)
cobinder_logo   <- plot_motif(cobinder_matrix)

Annotating conservation plot with motifs

## Adding motifs to the plot:
conservation_plot <- conservation_plot +
    annotation_custom(
        ggplotGrob(core_logo),
        xmin = core_segment$x, 
        xmax = core_segment$xend,
        ymin = 0.0005,
        ymax = round(max(df$value)/12, 2)) +
    annotation_custom(
        ggplotGrob(cobinder_logo),
        xmin = cobinder_segment$x,
        xmax = cobinder_segment$xend,
        ymin = 0.0005,
        ymax = round(max(df$value)/12, 2))
